/// Authoring guide call reminder injected via `{authoring_guide_prelude}`.
///
/// Canonical form used by ingest/create and enrich/research.
/// setup/create uses the same placeholder but the setup instruction has a
/// shorter opening sentence before it — both resolve to this text.
pub(crate) const AUTHORING_GUIDE_PRELUDE: &str = "\
IMPORTANT: Before creating any documents, call factbase(op='authoring_guide') to learn the required \
document format (temporal tags, inline [^N] footnotes, structure). Do NOT use a ## Sources section \
— every fact needs an inline [^N] citation immediately after it and a [^N]: definition at the \
bottom after a --- separator.";

/// Write-complete-facts reminder injected via `{write_complete_rule}`.
///
/// Appears in setup/create, ingest/create, and enrich/research.
pub(crate) const WRITE_COMPLETE_RULE: &str = "\
⚠️ WRITE COMPLETE FACTS: When you write a fact line, complete it immediately — citation, @t[] tag, \
and precise language. Do not defer to a resolve pass. If the source is in front of you (a file, URL, \
verse, record), cite it now. Facts written without citations and temporal tags become review queue \
debt that costs significantly more to resolve later than to write correctly up front.";

/// Post-write scan reminder injected via `{scan_after_write}`.
///
/// Canonical form used by ingest/create, enrich/research, correct/fix, and transition/apply.
/// Normalised from 17 slightly different variants — all said the same thing.
pub(crate) const SCAN_AFTER_WRITE: &str = "\
⚠️ AFTER WRITING: Always call factbase(op='scan') after modifying or creating documents. \
This verifies quality, indexes new facts, and generates review questions. Without scan, your \
changes are not validated.";

/// Applicability check injected via `{applicability_check}`.
///
/// Identical block in DEFAULT_RESOLVE_ANSWER_INTRO_INSTRUCTION and
/// DEFAULT_IMPROVE_RESOLVE_INSTRUCTION.
pub(crate) const APPLICABILITY_CHECK: &str = "\
⚠️ APPLICABILITY CHECK — ask this before answering any question:\n\
\"Does answering this question improve this fact, given its domain and question type?\"\n\
\n\
- If YES: answer it using the instructions below.\n\
- If NO (the question type doesn't apply to this fact in this domain): mark the fact as reviewed for that type and explain why.\n\
  Add `<!-- reviewed:X:DATE -->` (where X = p/t/a/s) to the fact line in the document.\n\
  Answer the question with confidence='verified': \"not-applicable: [reason — e.g. 'permanent game attribute, no meaningful date', 'genre vocabulary, no quantifiable equivalent']\"\n\
  This suppresses the question for 180 days without requiring a fake answer.\n\
\n\
Examples where the answer is NO:\n\
- precision on \"excellent Pyro DPS character\" in a game guide → genre vocabulary, no numeric benchmark\n\
- temporal on \"Diluc's element is Pyro\" → permanent attribute, a date adds no value\n\
- precision on \"notable philanthropist\" in a biography → editorial judgment, not quantifiable\n\
Examples where the answer is YES:\n\
- precision on \"heavy casualties in the battle\" in a WWII KB → casualty count IS available and improves the fact\n\
- temporal on \"founded the company\" → a founding date is meaningful and findable";

/// Temporal tag answer rules injected via `{temporal_tag_resolve}` into resolve/improve instructions.
///
/// Canonical resolve-time temporal guidance: what format the answer must take,
/// range vs. single-date rules, static-fact handling, and rejected dismissals.
/// Used by: DEFAULT_RESOLVE_ANSWER_INTRO_INSTRUCTION, DEFAULT_IMPROVE_RESOLVE_INSTRUCTION,
/// VARIANT_TYPE_EVIDENCE_INTRO, VARIANT_RESEARCH_BATCH_INTRO.
pub(crate) const TEMPORAL_TAG_RESOLVE: &str = "\
TEMPORAL — fact line has no @t[...] tag.\n\
→ First apply the applicability check above.\n\
→ If applicable: MUST include the tag: \"@t[YYYY] per [source] ([reference]); verified YYYY-MM-DD\"\n\
→ Ranges: @t[YYYY..YYYY], ongoing: @t[YYYY..], BCE: @t[-480] or @t[=480 BCE] (single dates only)\n\
→ IMPORTANT: = is for SINGLE exact dates only. Ranges use bare dates: @t[2020..2024], NOT @t[=2020..=2024]\n\
→ Unknown date: @t[?] (only when truly unfindable)\n\
→ WRONG: \"well-known\", \"static\", \"doesn't change\" — rejected, no audit trail\n\
→ TEMPORAL (static facts): If a fact describes a permanently fixed attribute (e.g., a character's element in a game, a historical constant, a definitional property) and you have verified it will not change, mark `<!-- reviewed:t:YYYY-MM-DD -->` instead of @t[?]. Include reasoning: \"temporal: permanent attribute — [source]\"\n\
→ MALFORMED TAG: If the existing fact has a malformed @t[] tag (narrative label like @t[infancy] or @t[burning bush]): replace it with valid syntax (@t[YYYY], @t[YYYY..YYYY], or @t[?]) or remove it entirely if the fact is permanently undatable. Do not leave malformed tags in place.\
";

/// Canonical confidence level definitions injected via `{confidence_levels}`.
///
/// Full version from DEFAULT_RESOLVE_ANSWER_INTRO_INSTRUCTION — includes self-consistent
/// fact pattern, author: prohibition rules, and deferred guidance.
/// Replaces abbreviated inline blocks in both resolve answer instructions.
pub(crate) const CONFIDENCE_LEVELS: &str = "\
CONFIDENCE LEVELS:\n\
- **verified**: You consulted an external source and found confirmation. Include the source reference (URL, document ID, API response, etc.). Use confidence='verified' (or omit â it's the default). These answers WILL be applied.\n\
  - For self-consistent facts (two facts in the same document that don't actually contradict): use `verified: [document-internal: <reason why both facts are consistent]`. Example: `verified: [document-internal: both facts share the same date @t[2020-11], start date and join date being identical is expected and not a contradiction]`\n\
  - For terminology questions where you can find a citation: use `verified: <URL> (accessed YYYY-MM-DD) â <explanation>`. Example: `verified: https://docs.aws.amazon.com/secretsmanager/latest/userguide/intro.html (accessed 2026-03-20) â Secrets Manager stores cryptographic keys; \"key\" here means authentication credential`\n\
- **author**: The KB owner has explicitly told you in this session to mark something as author-confirmed. Use confidence='author' ONLY when the human has explicitly instructed you to do so in a direct message like \"mark this as author-verified.\" Format: 'author: [what the KB owner stated]'. These answers ARE applied and flagged as author-confirmed.\n\
  â ï¸ `author:` IS PROHIBITED in automated/non-interactive resolve runs. You may ONLY use `author:` when a human has explicitly instructed you to in this session via a direct message like \"mark this as author-verified.\"\n\
  â ï¸ NEVER self-authorize: do NOT use author: because you think a fact is correct, because you can reason it out from document context, because the human said 'these facts are all correct', or to clear the queue faster. Being confident in an answer does NOT qualify. Reasoning from document context does NOT qualify.\n\
  If you cannot find an external citation: use `verified: [document-internal: <reason>]` for self-consistent facts, or `deferred` if you need external confirmation.\n\
- **deferred**: You researched and could not confirm, OR the human has not explicitly authorized author:. Prefix with 'defer:' and explain what you tried. A good defer with reasoning is better than a confident guess without evidence. Deferring means you did your job â you researched and couldn't confirm.";

pub(crate) const EVIDENCE_REQUIREMENT: &str = "\
⚠️ EVIDENCE REQUIREMENT: Every answer MUST cite an external source (URL, document ID, book, API \
result, or other verifiable reference). 'Well-known historical fact', 'still accurate', or \
'training data' are NOT acceptable evidence. If you cannot find an external source confirming the \
claim, DEFER — that is the correct action.\n\
\n\
⚠️ DATE REQUIRED: Every verified answer must include a date. Use the access date if no publication \
date is available: \"verified: https://... (accessed YYYY-MM-DD)\". There is no valid reason to \
omit a date — if you accessed the source, you know today's date.\n\
- ❌ BAD: \"verified: https://docs.aws.amazon.com/... — confirms feature exists\" (no date)\n\
- ✅ GOOD: \"verified: https://docs.aws.amazon.com/... (accessed 2026-03-20) — confirms feature exists\"";

